<font color="#FF0000">GUILTY?</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 18 15:01:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
In the past few years more than a few 'correct aged' men have told me they served in Vietnam.  When asked their unit or base, an &quot;I can't remember&quot; was the first indication that it was BS.  The second was when they'd break into a story so full of bravado and BS that John Wayne himself would be proud.  Quite frankly, I'd rather buy someone who protested the war a steak dinner than these people the bun for a hotdog.  If you were there, &quot;Welcome home and thank you, for being at my side&quot;.  If you weren't there, and had nothing to do with why you weren't, there's nothing to feel guilty about.  It was an experience perhaps you weren't ment to deal with.  Admittedly, there are times when I feel guilty, though ashamed might be a better word, over things I did in Vietnam.  But I consider torment over something which happened 30 years ago to be counter-productive.  If I could bring back those instances, erase them from ever happening I most assuredly would.  I can't - you can't - they can't. I exist with the nightmares because I have to.  They are burned into my memory.  Be glad, not sorry. <br><br>
If you openly protested, if anything at all, it proves that regardless of it's shortcomings, America is still the greatest Country there is.  I have a photograph, taken during one of the main protests, at our main intersection here in Rochester NY. There's an NVA flag flying from a lamp post - would that have been able to have happened in any other Country!?  Did it boil my blood to see it there?  You're damned right it did!  However, with the years has come maturity.  It was a time of turmoil for each of us. The wounds have scarred over, tempers have softened and hopefully, a greater understanding for each other prevails.
<p><code>-- mgiambra@frontiernet.com  (Zingara) </code><p>


